Semantic Segmentation. We evaluate HPTQ on Pascal VOC [44] using 
DeepLab V3 3 [6] with MobileNetV2 [29] as a backbone.

Table 4: Semantic segmentation on Pascal VOC [44] using DeepLab V3 with Mo-
bileNetV2 [29] as a backbone. F-mIoU is the floating point mean Intersection-
over-Union (mIoU) and Q-mIoU is the mIoU of the quantized model.

Table 5: Object detection results with HPTQ on COCO [45] using MobileNetV2 
[29] and ResNet50 [1] as backbones. F-mAP is the floating point mAP and Q-
mAP is the mAP of the quantized model.

Table 6: ImageNet classification [34] accuracy with HPTQ in four cases: full 
floating-point, activation quantization, weight quantization and both activation 
and weight quantization.

Table 7: ImageNet classification [34] accuracy with activations quantized using 
different threshold selection methods (weights are in floating point).

Table 8: The accuracy influence of the different activation quantization methods 
used by HPTQ for ImageNet classification [34] when keeping all weights in 
floating point. Baseline is quantization with no-clipping thresholds, +Eq. means 
adding max channel equalization, +MSE Th. means replacing the no-clipping 
thresholds with MSE and +z-score means applying z-score outlier removal.

Table 9: ImageNet classification accuracy [34] using HPTQ with and without 
SNC of MobileNetV1 [2] trained with different non-linear functions.

Table 10: ImageNet classification [34] accuracy with weights quantized using 
different threshold selection methods (activations are in floating point).

Table 11: The incremental influence of applying per-channel threshold selec-
tion (Per ch.) and bias correction (Bias corr.) on ImageNet [34] classification 
accuracy. Baseline means quantization with MSE threshold applied per tensor.
